<TITLE> Mortar at Iran fuel station fails to explode-report </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TEHRAN, July 3 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A mortar shell was fired at a petrol station in Tehran but it failed to explode, an Iranian news agency said on Tuesday, a week after more than a dozen pump stations were torched in protest at gasoline rationing. In a bid to curb costly imports of fuel, the oil-rich country last Wednesday introduced rationing, sparking chaotic and at times violent scenes. One Iranian report last week said 19 petrol stations were set alight in the capital. The situation has since calmed down, but the semi-official Fars News Agency said a mortar shell was fired late on Monday at a petrol station in eastern Tehran. "This mortar shell which was fired from an unknown place failed to function after hitting the fuel station," Fars quoted an informed source as saying, without elaborating. Bomb disposal experts arrived to the scene to defuse the device. Iran lacks domestic refining capacity, forcing it to import 40 percent of its gasoline needs, even though it sits on the world's second largest oil reserves. Many Iranians regard cheap and abundant fuel as a national rig
